<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="310" pageId="6" pageNumber="309" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="309">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="310" pageId="6" pageNumber="309">
Previously, the only known specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnavuori" authorityYear="1979" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Phlogis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="310" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mirabilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="310">
<pageBreakToken pageId="7" pageNumber="310" start="start">Phlogis</pageBreakToken>
mirabilis
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was the female type from Cameroon. A male specimen from Central African Republic is tentatively considered as conspecific to the type-specimen, based on distribution, external morphology, and size (7.4 mm). The male genitalia of this specimen agree with those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yang" authorityYear="1991" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Chouious" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="310" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="310">Chouious</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the characters described for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnavuori" authorityYear="1979" lsidName="" pageId="7" pageNumber="310" rank="tribe" tribe="Phlogisini">Phlogisini</taxonomicName>
. However, this male can be easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yang" authorityYear="1991" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Chouious" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="310" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="310">Chouious</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because its: (1) pygofer lobe lacks the deep concavity on the dorsal margin, (2) aedeagus lacks ventral atrial processes, but has paired apical recurved processes; and (3) anal tube segment X has posterolateral paired processes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="310" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="310">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="310">
Cameroon (
<bibRefCitation author="Linnavuori, R" journalOrPublisher="Entomotaxonomia" pageId="19" pageNumber="322" refId="B13" refString="Linnavuori, R, 1979. Revision of African Cicadellidae, part I. Revue de Zoologie africaine 93: 647-747." title="Revision of African Cicadellidae, part I. Revue de Zoologie africaine 93: 647 - 747." year="1979">Linnavuori 1979</bibRefCitation>
) and Central African Republic [
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="310">new record</emphasis>
].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
